          "body": "Verse 15 deserves its own segment because it has been used for centuries as a touchstone of faith under pressure and simultaneously misread when extracted from context. The verse is not a quiet submission to providence — it is a confession made in the context of legal combat. Job is not saying 'I will accept whatever God does and not complain.' He is saying: 'Even if God kills me in the process of this argument, I will not stop bringing the argument.' The hope (*yachal*) is hope directed *at* God — not hope that God will make the suffering stop, but hope that God is the kind of being before whom the truth can be spoken. Calvin found in this verse the seed of the resurrection faith: the one who hopes in God even through death must believe that God's justice extends beyond death. Jonathan Edwards read it as the supreme test of whether love for God is disinterested — would you love God if He gave you nothing? Job's answer is yes, even if He takes your life. The verse does not resolve the problem of suffering; it refuses to let the problem of suffering dissolve the relationship with God. D. A. Carson's observation is apt: the sufferer who continues to pray angry prayers is closer to God than the one who stops praying altogether."
